">per person on twin sharing<\/p>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=&#8221;gt-book-section&#8221; width=&#8221;1\/2&#8243;][vc_btn title=&#8221;Book Now&#8221; style=&#8221;custom&#8221; custom_background=&#8221;#f99914&#8243; custom_text=&#8221;#212221&#8243; size=&#8221;sm&#8221; align=&#8221;center&#8221; button_block=&#8221;true&#8221; el_id=&#8221;gt-booking&#8221; el_class=&#8221;gt-theme-button&#8221;][vc_btn title=&#8221;View All Packages&#8221; style=&#8221;custom&#8221; custom_background=&#8221;#40e0d0&#8243; custom_text=&#8221;#ffffff&#8221; size=&#8221;sm&#8221; align=&#8221;center&#8221; button_block=&#8221;true&#8221; el_class=&#8221;gt-theme-button&#8221; link=&#8221;url:%23gt_all_packages&#8221;][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][\/vc_column][\/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width=&#8221;2\/3&#8243;][vc_row_inner el_class=&#8221;gt-package-slider&#8221;][vc_column_inner][vc_images_carousel images=&#8221;30313,30309,30310,30308,30311,30312&#8243; img_size=&#8221;full&#8221; onclick=&#8221;link_no&#8221; autoplay=&#8221;yes&#8221; hide_pagination_control=&#8221;yes&#8221; wrap=&#8221;yes&#8221;][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class=&#8221;gt-slider-bottom-section&#8221;][vc_column_inner width=&#8221;3\/4&#8243;][vc_acf field_group=&#8221;29256&#8243; field_from_29256=&#8221;field_6458cb457e4af&#8221; show_label=&#8221;yes&#8221; el_class=&#8221;gt-acf-general&#8221;][vc_acf field_group=&#8221;29256&#8243; field_from_29256=&#8221;field_6458cb3a7e4ae&#8221; show_label=&#8221;yes&#8221; el_class=&#8221;gt-acf-general&#8221;][vc_acf field_group=&#8221;29256&#8243; field_from_29256=&#8221;field_6458cb2d7e4ad&#8221; show_label=&#8221;yes&#8221; el_class=&#8221;gt-acf-general&#8221;][\/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=&#8221;1\/4&#8243;][vc_btn title=&#8221;View All Packages&#8221; style=&#8221;custom&#8221; custom_background=&#8221;#f99914&#8243; custom_text=&#8221;#212221&#8243; size=&#8221;sm&#8221; align=&#8221;center&#8221; button_block=&#8221;true&#8221; el_class=&#8221;gt-theme-button&#8221; link=&#8221;url:%23gt_all_packages&#8221;][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][\/vc_column][vc_column width=&#8221;1\/3&#8243;][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=&#8221;gt-detail-table&#8221;][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;South India\u2019s No.1 Travel Brand&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|font_size:16px|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_separator][vc_column_text el_class=&#8221;gt-detail-field&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div>UAE Dirham<\/div>\n<div>Currency Name<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text el_class=&#8221;gt-detail-field&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div>19\u00b0C to 36\u00b0C<\/div>\n<div>Climate in Dubai<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text el_class=&#8221;gt-detail-field&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div>November - March<\/div>\n<div>Best Season to Visit Dubai<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text el_class=&#8221;gt-detail-field&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div>Arabic, English<\/div>\n<div>Languages Speaking<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=&#8221;gt-tips-section&#8221;][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Essential Tips for Travelling to the Dubai&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|font_size:16px|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;]        <div class=\"title-insta\">\r\n            <div class=\"st-img-icon\"><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.atwtravels.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/ATMs.png\" alt=\"\"><\/div>\r\n            <p class=\"text\">ATMs are readily accessible in all areas.<\/p>\r\n        <\/div>\r\n                <div class=\"title-insta\">\r\n            <div class=\"st-img-icon\"><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.atwtravels.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Credit-Cards.png\" alt=\"\"><\/div>\r\n            <p class=\"text\">Credit Cards are widely accepted.<\/p>\r\n        <\/div>\r\n                <div class=\"title-insta\">\r\n            <div class=\"st-img-icon\"><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.atwtravels.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Bank.png\" alt=\"\"><\/div>\r\n            <p class=\"text\">Finding a bank in Dubai is easy.<\/p>\r\n        <\/div>\r\n                <div class=\"title-insta\">\r\n            <div class=\"st-img-icon\"><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.atwtravels.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Drinking.png\" alt=\"\"><\/div>\r\n            <p class=\"text\">The legal drinking age in Dubai is 21.<\/p>\r\n        <\/div>\r\n                <div class=\"title-insta\">\r\n            <div class=\"st-img-icon\"><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.atwtravels.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Safest.png\" alt=\"\"><\/div>\r\n            <p class=\"text\">Dubai residents share a reputation for hospitality.<\/p>\r\n        <\/div>\r\n                <div class=\"title-insta\">\r\n            <div class=\"st-img-icon\"><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.atwtravels.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Prices.png\" alt=\"\"><\/div>\r\n            <p class=\"text\">Prices are typically cheaper in March to October.<\/p>\r\n        <\/div>\r\n                <div class=\"title-insta\">\r\n            <div class=\"st-img-icon\"><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.atwtravels.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Weekend.png\" alt=\"\"><\/div>\r\n            <p class=\"text\">Dubai has a Different Weekend: Friday and Saturday.<\/p>\r\n        <\/div>\r\n        [\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][\/vc_column][\/vc_row][vc_row el_class=&#8221;float-left&#8221; el_id=&#8221;gt_country_tour_details&#8221;][vc_column][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai &#8211; Visitors Statistics&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_row_inner css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1683352016764{padding-top: 40px !important;}&#8221;][vc_column_inner el_class=&#8221;border-design-right gt-horizontal-map gt-statistics&#8221; width=&#8221;1\/4&#8243;][vc_single_image image=&#8221;30314&#8243; img_size=&#8221;full&#8221; alignment=&#8221;center&#8221;][\/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=&#8221;border-design-right gt-statistics&#8221; width=&#8221;1\/4&#8243;][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Annually&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221; el_class=&#8221;gt_statistics_heading_sub&#8221;][vc_column_text el_class=&#8221;tour_gt_number&#8221;]<span class=\"no_desig_gth\">1,40,00,000<\/span>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text el_class=&#8221;count_no_tour_people&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div class=\"list_gt_div\">\n<div class=\"gt_tour_male\">\n<p class=\"gth_tourm_head\"><span class=\"gth_count_he\">Male<\/span><span class=\"gth_countper\">51%<\/span><\/p>\n<\/div>\n<div class=\"gt_tour_fem\">\n<p class=\"gth_tourm_head\"><span class=\"gth_count_he\">Female<\/span><span class=\"gth_countper\">49%<\/span><\/p>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=&#8221;border-design-right gt-statistics&#8221; width=&#8221;1\/4&#8243;][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;By Purpose&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221; el_class=&#8221;gt_statistics_heading_sub&#8221;][vc_column_text el_class=&#8221;purpose_div&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div class=\"gthpurpose\">\n<div class=\"gthpurpose-img\"><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/gt-hoildays-couple-icon.png\" alt=\"tour package tourism\" \/><\/div>\n<div class=\"gthpurpose-block\">\n<p class=\"gthpurpose-title\">Couples<\/p>\n<p class=\"gthpurpose-text\">For Newlywed Vacations<\/p>\n<div class=\"progress\">\n<div class=\"progress-bar\" style=\"width: 55%;\"><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text el_class=&#8221;purpose_div&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div class=\"gthpurpose\">\n<div class=\"gthpurpose-img\"><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/gt-hoildays-family-icon.png\" alt=\"tour packages business\" \/><\/div>\n<div class=\"gthpurpose-block\">\n<p class=\"gthpurpose-title\">Family<\/p>\n<p class=\"gthpurpose-text\">For Family Vacations<\/p>\n<div class=\"progress\">\n<div class=\"progress-bar\" style=\"width: 35%;\"><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=&#8221;gt-statistics&#8221; width=&#8221;1\/4&#8243;][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Top Visitors from India&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221; el_class=&#8221;gt_statistics_heading_sub&#8221;][vc_column_text]<\/p>\n<div class=\"gt-top-city\">\n<p class=\"gt-top-city-list\">Bengaluru<\/p>\n<p class=\"gt-top-city-list\">Mumbai<\/p>\n<p class=\"gt-top-city-list\">India<\/p>\n<p class=\"gt-top-city-list\">Delhi<\/p>\n<p class=\"gt-top-city-list\">Hyderabad<\/p>\n<p class=\"gt-top-city-list\">Pune<\/p>\n<p class=\"gt-top-city-list\">Kolkata<\/p>\n<p class=\"gt-top-city-list\">Ahmedabad<\/p>\n<p class=\"gt-top-city-list\">Jaipur<\/p>\n<p class=\"gt-top-city-list\">Lucknow<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][\/vc_column][\/vc_row][vc_row css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1706236961480{margin-top: 20px !important;}&#8221; el_class=&#8221;float-left mob-m0&#8243; el_id=&#8221;package_div_section&#8221;][vc_column][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;All You Need to Know About Dubai Tour&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]With ATMs that dispense gold, ski slopes in the middle of the desert, and the police driving Bugattis, Lamborghini Aventadors, and Aston Martins, Dubai is a city of excesses. Did you know Burj Al Arab is decorated with over 19,000 square feet of 24-carat gold leaf? Guests at the Burj Al Arab Hotel are even offered 24-carat gold-coated iPads during check-in! No wonder Dubai is called The City of Gold. The city is no stranger to world records \u2013 Dubai has been awarded over 300 Guinness World Records.<\/p>\n<p>But it is also a city of contrasts. Even before Dubai became a modern architectural marvel, it had a thriving pearl diving industry. The Bur Dubai waterfront has beautifully preserved its culture and history. Al Bastakiya has several historic buildings, including the Al Fahidi Fort, the Dubai Museum, and the Sheikh Mohammed Centre for Cultural Understanding. [\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column][vc_column][vc_btn title=&#8221;Read More&#8221; align=&#8221;center&#8221; el_class=&#8221;readmoreBtn&#8221;][\/vc_column][\/vc_row][vc_row el_id=&#8221;readmoreLayer&#8221;][vc_column][vc_row_inner el_class=&#8221;hide_readless&#8221;][vc_column_inner][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Table of Content&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]<\/p>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"#about\">About Dubai<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"#essential-tips\">Essential Tips To Know Before Travelling To Dubai<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"#at-glance\">Dubai At A Glance<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"#top-reasons\">Top Reasons To Visit Dubai<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"#best-time-to-visit\">Best Time To Visit Dubai<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"#things-to-do\">Top Things To Do In Dubai<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"#places-to-visit\">Top Places To Visit In Dubai<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"#shopping\">Shopping In Dubai<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"#what-to-eat\">What To Eat In Dubai?<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;About Dubai&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221; el_id=&#8221;about&#8221;][vc_column_text]Dubai is the second largest emirate in the UAE and is often referred to as the Pearl of the Gulf. Dubai was originally divided into two parts and separated by Khor Dubai, a natural seawater inlet: Bur Dubai and Deira. Bur Dubai, along with Deira and Al Shingada, form part of Old Dubai. Of these, Al Shingada is the oldest neighbourhood where the rulers of Dubai once lived. The different places in Dubai get their name from their natural features. For instance, Al Muteena receives its name from the clayey soil in the area. Similarly, Al Hamriyah is called so because it is a coastal settlement for people from Sharjah. Old Dubai has several souks or traditional markets selling spices, gold, garments, and other items.<\/p>\n<p>New Dubai is in complete contrast to old parts of the city. It is modern well-structured, and it abounds with luxury. Some of the world\u2019s largest, longest, and most famous buildings are located in New Dubai. For instance, the Ibn Battuta Mall, Burj Khalifa, Dubai Mall, etc., are in New Dubai. Some places here include Downtown Dubai, Dubai Marina, Dubai Hills Estate, etc. [\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class=&#8221;hide_readless&#8221;][vc_column_inner][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Essential Tips To Know Before Travelling To Dubai&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221; el_id=&#8221;essential-tips&#8221;][vc_column_text]<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>Best season to visit Dubai \u2013 November to March.<\/li>\n<li>Hindi and English are commonly spoken, although Arabic is the official language of the UAE.<\/li>\n<li>Burj Khalifa is the most visited tourist attraction.<\/li>\n<li>Popular activities in Dubai \u2013 Shopping, desert safari, dhow dinner cruise, hot air balloon ride.<\/li>\n<li>Souvenirs to buy in Dubai \u2013 gold, spices, nuts, dates, attar, chocolates, electronics.<\/li>\n<li>Dress conservatively in public places. Don\u2019t swear or take alcohol in public.<\/li>\n<li>Shawarma, falafel, and biryani are among the cheapest food in Dubai.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai At A Glance&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221; el_id=&#8221;at-glance&#8221;][vc_column_text]<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>How many hours from India &#8211; ~4.5 hours<\/li>\n<li>Famous tourist attractions \u2013 Burj Khalifa, Dubai Mall, Dubai Fountain, Miracle Garden<\/li>\n<li>Things to do in Dubai \u2013 Desert safari, dhow cruise, Visiting the top deck of Burj Khalifa, Visting Dubai souk, Visiting Atlantis Aquaventure Waterpark, skydiving, ziplining<\/li>\n<li>Famous food to try \u2013 Shawarma, luqaimat, falafel, biryani<\/li>\n<li>Things you must try at least once in Dubai \u2013 Desert safari, camel racing at Al Marmoom, and deep diving in DeepDive Dubai.<\/li>\n<li>Famous attractions in Dubai \u2013 Burj Khalifa, Dubai Miracle Garden, Jumeirah Mosque, Al Fahidi Historic Neighbourhood, Dubai Mall<\/li>\n<li>Souvenirs to buy \u2013 spices, gold, attar, dates, electronic items<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class=&#8221;hide_readless&#8221; el_id=&#8221;top-reasons&#8221;][vc_column_inner][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Top Reasons To Visit Dubai&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]With its giant shopping malls, eclectic architecture, and majestic skyscrapers, Dubai is a fantasy land, attracting millions of tourists with luxurious and opulent lifestyles. But it\u2019s also a city of contrasts where working-class immigrants have set up shops to cater to their fellow countrymen. Case in point: Dubai is the best place outside India (or Pakistan) to satisfy your biryani cravings. Here are some of the reasons you must book a Dubai tour package today:[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai Is A Land Where Impossible Becomes Possible&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Dubai\u2019s ambitious rulers have taken it upon themselves to make the impossible possible. From ski slopes in the middle of a desert to deep diving in the world\u2019s deepest swimming pool to showcasing 50 million flowers and 250 million plants in a desert, Dubai is the best example of creating a new reality. It is the world\u2019s first and only country with a separate ministry to make impossible things happen \u2013the Ministry of Possibilities.<\/p>\n<p>From the tallest picture frame to the tallest building, the largest chocolate sculpture, and the world\u2019s largest fireworks display, Dubai is one of the world&#8217;s most innovative cities.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai Is An Entertainment Hub&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Dubai is the best place to sample international cuisine, thanks to its huge immigrant population. From fancy restaurants serving French and Japanese cuisine to local shops selling biryani, Kerala fish curry, and pad Thai, there are plenty of options depending on your budget. You can visit the Dubai Art Centre DUCTAC to enjoy theatre, live music or a dance show, quad biking or sandboarding on the Arabian Desert, skydiving, a dhow cruise on Dubai Marina, or the view from The Palm.<\/p>\n<p>From Legoland and Bollywood Parks to Wild Wadi Waterpark, Aquaventure, and the IMG Worlds of Adventure, there are plenty of theme parks where you can have a fun time with kids. If you\u2019re an adventure enthusiast, go deep diving in the world\u2019s deepest swimming pool. You can enjoy skiing, shark diving, and zip lining, take a hot air balloon ride, take a helicopter ride for a bird\u2019s eye view of the city, or enjoy a desert safari. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai Is A Shopaholic\u2019s Dream Destination&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]From shopping at the world\u2019s biggest and best malls to budget markets, Dubai has plenty of shopping options. The Dubai Mall is one of the world\u2019s largest malls with international brands like Bloomingdale\u2019s, Zara, H&amp;M, and Dior. And if you\u2019d like to enjoy European-style street shopping, head to City Walk.<\/p>\n<p>If you are looking for budget shopping places, head to the Dubai Waterfront Market, the many souks in Bur Dubai, Karama Centre, and Dragon Mart. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai Is The Most Over-The-Top Place On Earth&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]America may be about everything bigger and better, but Dubai is about opulence. It\u2019s the only place in the world where the police drive supercars like Aston Martins, Bugattis, and Lambhorgini Avendetors. Spa treatments at one of Jumeirah\u2019s spas involve 24-carat gold and even pure platinum. There\u2019s also an ice cream caf\u00e9 that costs $900 per scoop, which includes Italian truffles, saffron, and edible gold.<\/p>\n<p>There are cocktails made with diamonds, hotel rooms built underwater, and the world\u2019s most expensive biryani. The world\u2019s most expensive cupcake is sold at $1000 per cupcake and is made using Ugandian vanilla beans, strawberries, and Italian chocolate. All of these are then decorated with 24-carat edible gold.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai Is The City Of World Records&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]With over 300 world records registered in the Guinness Book of World Records, Dubai is one of the biggest, best, and craziest cities in the world. Some well-known records include The Burj Khalifa, Ain Dubai, the world\u2019s largest observation wheel, Dubai Frame, the world\u2019s largest frame, and Dubai Mall, the world\u2019s largest mall.<\/p>\n<p>Some lesser-known marvels on the record list include the world\u2019s tallest chocolate sculpture, Maze Tower, the world\u2019s largest vertical maze, the world\u2019s longest handmade chain, and the longest painting. The Dubai Fountain is the world\u2019s largest fountain, and DeepDive is the world\u2019s deepest swimming pool, containing 14 million litres of water. With 50 million natural flowers, the Dubai Miracle Garden is the largest flower arrangement in the world.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai Is A Modern, Multicultural City&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]With over 80% of its population comprising immigrants, Dubai is home to people from over 200 nationalities. It\u2019s one of the few places where Hindi and English are more commonly spoken than Arabic, the local language. Besides Hindi and English, you\u2019ll also find people speaking Malayalam. The rulers of Dubai have consciously adopted religious tolerance, ensuring that people of all faiths live together in harmony. Hindus are the third largest religious group in the UAE, just behind Christians and Muslims.<\/p>\n<p>There are Hindu temples, gurudwaras, churches, Buddhist monasteries, and even a Jewish synagogue in Dubai. The UAE is one of the few countries in the world with a separate civil law on marriage, divorce, custody, and inheritance for non-Muslims. [\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class=&#8221;hide_readless&#8221; el_id=&#8221;best-time-to-visit&#8221;][vc_column_inner][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Best Time To Visit Dubai&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]With an arid desert climate, Dubai has winter and summer seasons. Naturally, the best time to visit the city is from November to March, when the temperatures average 25 \u00b0C and nighttime temperatures can be as low as 5\u00b0C.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;November To March \u2013 The Best Time&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]The weather is cool, with temperatures dropping to early twenties and the nights being chilly. It\u2019s a little toasty in January, but since humidity is still low, the temperatures could be as low as 15\u00b0C. February is slightly hotter, yet pleasant. There could be a little rainfall and an occasional thunderstorm, but not long enough to dampen your holiday.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;What\u2019s Special About Visiting Dubai From November To March?&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h5|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Winter is also the best time to visit Dubai to experience the magic of the Dubai Festival. This shopping extravaganza takes place in December every year, attracting millions of tourists from around the world.<\/p>\n<p>The Dubai Design Week is celebrated in November, and tourists can explore the Dubai Design District for free and enjoy the local art scene, including art workshops, engaging talks, and even immersive design experiences. The city hosts the Dubai Jazz Festival around February, where the likes of Mariah Carey and John Legend perform at the Dubai Media City Amphitheatre.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;But Ticket Prices Are Expensive\u2026&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h5|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Winters aren\u2019t the cheapest time to explore Dubai. Flight tickets and hotel prices are expensive and must be booked ahead. December is undoubtedly the most expensive time to fly to Dubai, with ticket prices costing at least 30% more than the regular fare. While admission and entry rates are constant, hotel rates generally increase in winter, especially around Christmas and New Year. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;April To May \u2013 The Shoulder Season&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]The weather from April to May progressively transitions from pleasantly windy to hot within a few weeks. May is officially summer in Dubai, with temperatures soaring to 37\u00b0C and over 11 hours of sunlight. But you can still spend some time beside a swimming pool with a shade until noon. But it could get a little humid around this time. If you visit the city in April, the climate is pleasant enough to spend time on the beach. Temperatures average around 33\u00b0C during this time.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;What is special about visiting Dubai from April to May?&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h5|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]April is a great time to visit Dubai because of the Dubai Food Festival. The Children\u2019s International Film Festival is also held around this month, bringing families from around the world to the city. Since it\u2019s not too crowded, you don\u2019t have to worry about long queues outside prominent tourist attractions in April and May.<\/p>\n<p>May isn\u2019t a favourable time to visit the city, but it is also the least crowded and the cheapest time to explore Dubai. Agreed, people will warn you about the scorching heat, but if your itinerary includes indoor tourist attractions, there\u2019s nothing to worry about. All indoor entertainment places have air conditioning and are comfortable enough. You cannot walk to the different places since it is extremely hot in May, but there are enough transport options.<\/p>\n<p>Another advantage of choosing Dubai tour packages around April and May is the cheap hotel rates and the huge shopping discounts throughout the city. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;But Dubai Can Be Humid Around This Time&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h5|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Even if you can manage the heat, the humidity in the air will get to you. Remember to wear light clothes and drink plenty of water to stay hydrated.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;June to August \u2013 Summer Season&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]The summer season is considered one of the worst seasons to visit Dubai for a reason. Temperatures can reach 45\u00b0C during these months, and the average low could be around 30\u00b0C. Humidity could range from 50% to 60% from June to August. It\u2019s too hot even to step outside, let alone lounge on the beach or near the swimming pool.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;What\u2019s Special About Visiting Dubai From June To August?&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h5|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]If you\u2019re visiting Dubai for shopping, don\u2019t let the summer stop you. Hotels and airlines offer great discounts and added benefits, like complimentary breakfast and free laundry services during the summer. Indoor attractions like shopping malls and indoor theme parks are a great way to escape the scorching sun. During summer, you can visit Ski Dubai within The Dubai Mall of the Emirates, IMG Worlds of Adventure, and KidZania.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;The Heat Can Be Exhausting&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h5|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Heat exhaustion and heat strokes are some of the risks of travelling to Dubai during the harsh summer months. Remember to stay hydrated and avoid direct sunlight for long. If you\u2019re sweating profusely or feel nauseous, move to a shady place quickly to prevent fainting.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;September To October \u2013 Shoulder Season&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]September to October are transition months, and the weather ranges from hot to warm. The average temperature is around 39\u00b0C, but the temperature drops by around five degrees in October. You still have an average of 10 hours of daylight to enjoy the different tourist attractions and even possibly spend some time on the beach.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;What\u2019s Special About Visiting Dubai In September To October?&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h5|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Agreed, it is hot around this time but visitors don\u2019t arrive until November, so the places are less crowded. There are quite a few entertainment events planned around this time. For instance, The Dubai Home Festival is celebrated in September across Dubai. You can buy furniture and home d\u00e9cor items at discounted prices, participate in raffle draws, and even participate in interior decoration workshops.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai Can Be Pretty Hot From September To October&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h5|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Remember to wear light cotton clothes and carry enough sunblock. Carry a water bottle with you to stay hydrated. If you\u2019re travelling with kids, waiting until the evenings before hitting the beach is best.[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text]<strong>Ramadan is an important month for Muslims. They observe fast from sunrise to sunset and practice general abstinence. Earlier, restaurants had to blackout windows, and the general public was banned from eating in public during Ramadan. This is no longer the case, but business hours are open for fewer hours. Also, eating in public is socially unacceptable, though not illegal. Dress modestly and avoid public drinking or eating.<\/strong>[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class=&#8221;hide_readless&#8221; el_id=&#8221;things-to-do&#8221;][vc_column_inner][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Top Things To Do In Dubai&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Dubai blends the old and new beautifully, giving you a variety of activities to enjoy and explore in the city. If you are looking for Dubai tour packages that delicately balance its cultural heritage and history with modern architecture and futuristic tourist attractions. Some of the things you must explore in the city include:[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Enjoy View From The Observation Deck In Burj Khalifa&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]The Burj Khalifa is one of Dubai\u2019s most visited tourist attractions. The building has two observation decks \u2013 Level 125 at 456 metres and Level 124 at 452 metres. You could also choose the At The Top Sky package, which includes Level 148 at 555 metres. The Sky Lounge includes refreshments and a guided tour by a Guest Ambassador. On Level 125, you can step onto the open-air terrace and experience an augmented reality experience that simulates the feel of glass cracking under your feet as you walk on the glass floor. On Level 124, you\u2019ll enjoy a 360\u00b0 view of the city\u2019s glittering skyline from the viewing telescope and the floor-to-ceiling glass walls.<\/p>\n<p>But a panoramic view of the city isn\u2019t the only thing that\u2019s special about Burj Khalifa. You\u2019ll be travelling on the world\u2019s fastest elevators, which can reach the observation deck in just a minute.<\/p>\n<p>The sunrise\/sunset experience on the Burj Khalifa is the most expensive, but it\u2019s definitely worth the money. You\u2019ll need around 90 to 120 minutes to enjoy the entire Burj Khalifa experience. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Desert Safari&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Desert safaris are undoubtedly one of the most important aspects of every Dubai tour package. They are based on the traditional Bedouin experience when the Bedouins travelled the vast expanses of the Arabian desert using their ingenuity and knowledge of their environment. Today, tourists can enjoy a wholesome experience with camel riding, cultural performances, and even a BBQ dinner. Depending on your package, the experience could include fire shows, henna painting, belly dancing, quad biking, horse riding, sandboarding, falcon interaction, and dune bashing on a 4&#215;4. You can also stay overnight in a Bedouin tent, only to be woken up to the sights of a beautiful sunrise.<\/p>\n<p>When booking a desert safari, check what\u2019s included in the package. You can also ask for a guide to explain the different elements in the package and understand more about Bedouin history. And if you\u2019re a vegetarian, make sure you inform in advance. You can opt for a private desert safari or a group package, depending on your budget. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dhow Cruise&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]The coastal tribespeople traditionally used dhows to ferry heavy items along Dubai Creek. While they\u2019re not as much in use as they were centuries ago, you\u2019ll still find a few around Bur Dubai, the UAE\u2019s original trading hub. Today, these dhows are motorised and redesigned to ferry tourists along the Dubai Marina. Typical dhow cruises include a 5-star buffet, unlimited refreshments, tanura dance, and sightseeing.<\/p>\n<p>Some of the places covered in a typical dhow cruise include Dubai Marina, the old souks of Bur Dubai, the glistening skyline along the Marina and other landmarks. You can also celebrate special events like birthdays, anniversaries, and annual day parties on a dhow cruise by booking the entire charter for yourself and friends. Most dhow cruises can range from 90 minutes to up to 2 hours, depending on the package chosen. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Go Shopping&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Dubai is a shopping mecca for locals and tourists. With world-class malls and shopping complexes home to the world\u2019s best luxury and high-street food, you can buy anything on any budget. While The Dubai Mall and other places are great places to shop for branded clothes, the old souks are great for budget shopping. You can buy gold, spices, clothes, attar, and other items for a steal in these markets.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Things To Do In Dubai If You\u2019re Adventurous&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]While Dubai is a family destination, there are plenty of things for youngsters to enjoy and experience. You can sign up for a skydiving experience, deep diving, ziplining, snorkelling, shark diving, and flyboarding. If you don\u2019t know how to swim, how about walking with the sharks in the safety of a cage? [\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class=&#8221;hide_readless&#8221; el_id=&#8221;places-to-visit&#8221;][vc_column_inner][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Top Places To Visit In Dubai&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Burj Khalifa&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]The Burj Khalifa is the largest building in the world, soaring over Dubai and is nearly three times as tall as the Eiffel Tower. The building holds six other world records \u2013 for the tallest freestanding structure in the world, the highest number of storeys in the world, and the tallest service elevator in the world, among others. Enjoy a panoramic city view from the Burj Khalifa or high tea in the Sky Lounge on the 148th floor. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai Aquarium And Underwater Zoo&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]The Dubai Aquarium is the world\u2019s largest suspended aquarium. It houses over 140 species, including 300 types of sharks, sea horses, jellyfish, penguins, and giant groupers. The aquarium has one of the world&#8217;s largest collections of sand tiger sharks. Visitors can walk through the 48-metre tunnel providing a 270\u00b0view of the aquarium, which is 11 metres below the tank&#8217;s surface. Some other attractions in the aquarium include shark diving, a glass-bottom ride, and walking with sharks in a cage.<\/p>\n<p>You can also take a behind-the-scenes tour of the Dubai Aquarium to witness the staff feeding and caring for the marine animals. If you\u2019re interested in underwater photography, the Dubai Aquarium is a great place. Depending on the package you choose, you will need around 2 to 3 hours to enjoy the Dubai Aquarium experience. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai Miracle Garden&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]This is the world\u2019s largest natural flower garden, displaying over 150 million flowers spread over 72,000 square metres. The flowers, ranging from sunflowers and marigolds to petunias and tulips, are shipped from all over the world. It also holds the world record for the largest vertical garden. There\u2019s a separate butterfly garden with a collection of 15,000 butterflies in climate-controlled domes within the garden.<\/p>\n<p>You must visit the Dubai Miracle Garden even if you have visited it before because the garden\u2019s theme changes every year, and it has an entirely different look and feel depending on the season\u2019s theme.<\/p>\n<p>You will need around 3 to 4 hours, depending on the package chosen and the attractions you cover. The best time to visit the Miracle Garden is from November to March, when the flowers are in full bloom. Also, the garden is closed during summer thanks to the scorching sun. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Museum of the Future&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]The Dubai Museum of the Future is an ode to Dubai\u2019s futuristic ambitions and the headquarters for the city\u2019s Great Arab Minds initiative. The building is designed as an asymmetrical torus clad in steel and glass. It was featured on National Geographic as one of the 14 most beautiful museums in the world. The museum\u2019s striking exterior is as beautiful as the interior, where visitors can experience a range of next-generation solutions, including Tomorrow Today and Future Heroes.<\/p>\n<p>It is a living museum where experts brainstorm solutions to the world&#8217;s biggest problems. You\u2019ll need 3 to 4 hours to explore the museum, which has several cafes and restaurants where you can take a snack break. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]The Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque is in Abu Dhabi. Still, it is often included in most Dubai tour packages because of its architectural work and Islamic art that blends different Islamic architectural schools. Materials were shipped from all over the world to build this mosque. While marble was shipped from Italy, India, and Macedonia, carpets were imported from Iran, and Swarovski crystals for the chandelier were imported from Germany. The wool for the rug came from New Zealand.<\/p>\n<p>The mosque is open to all non-Muslim visitors, but they must dress respectfully and modestly. Women must cover their heads with a scarf or wear a traditional abaya, available for rent. Entry to the mosque is free.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Al Fahidi Historical Neighborhood&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]<\/p>\n<p>The Al Fahidi Historical Neighbourhood District is a gateway to Dubai\u2019s past and an essential aspect of UAE\u2019s identity. The entire neighbourhood covers around 38,000 square metres and extends for about 300 metres along Dubai Creek. While the neighbourhood hosts many buildings, including museums, art galleries, and cultural centres, The Al Fahidi Fort is the highlight of this place. It was built in 1787 using coral and shells cemented together with lime to guard the landward approaches to the city. The fort was converted into a museum to showcase the city\u2019s history and cultural heritage. Don\u2019t miss the Al Shindagha Museum to understand Dubai\u2019s lively past and the life of an average Emirati centuries ago.<\/p>\n<p>Another highlight of this place is the Barajeel, or high air tower, made using traditional materials like stone, gypsum, teak, and sandalwood. These wind towers cool the house, ridding it of warm air and bringing in cool breeze. There are also galleries depicting Emirati life before oil wealth transformed the nation. This includes traditional Emirati homes, mosques, souks, date farms, etc. [\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Old Dubai &amp; Souk Tour&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]You cannot appreciate Dubai\u2019s transformation without understanding its exciting past. At ATW Travels, our Dubai tour packages are designed to cover the city\u2019s heritage and culture. The areas we cover in Old Dubai include Deira, Al Bastakiya, Bur Dubai, Old City Wall, and Al Seef. Deira is one of Dubai\u2019s oldest neighbourhoods, famous for its age-old souks, the Gold Souk, the Spice Souk, and the Perfume Souk. The Al Mamzar Beach Park is great for relaxing with friends and family.<\/p>\n<p>Depending on how long you plan to tour Dubai, we can cover some of Dubai\u2019s best theme parks, including the Wild Wadi Waterpark, Legoland Dubai, Motiongate, and Atlantis Aquaventure. A typical half-day Dubai city tour will include visiting Burj Al Arab, Jumeirah Mosque, Jumeirah Beach, and the Sheikh Mohammed Palace. [\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class=&#8221;hide_readless&#8221; el_id=&#8221;shopping&#8221;][vc_column_inner][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Shopping In Dubai&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Dubai is the ultimate shopping destination, irrespective of your budget and what you want. You can buy anything from gold and spices to garments, perfumes, and electronics in the city. It was probably the first city in the world to have its shopping festival! The malls in Dubai aren\u2019t just any other place for shopping \u2013 given the scorching heat outside, it only makes sense that people socialise, eat, and entertain their kids within the mall. Typical malls have theatres, art galleries, aquariums, and even mosques. Some of the best places to shop in Dubai include:[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Mall of the Emirates&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Mall of the Emirates was inaugurated in 2005 in Downtown Dubai. Besides shopping at one of its high-end stores, you can go skiing in Ski Dubai, enjoy an imaginative adventure at Dreamscape, or dine at one of the many dining outlets in the mall.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Dubai Mall&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Dubai Mall was inaugurated in 2008 and is located in Downtown Dubai. You can shop at one of its 1200 retail stores, dine at one of its 200 restaurants and cafes, spend some time at KidZania, or explore marine animals at the Dubai Aquarium and Underwater Zoo.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Ibn Battuta Mall&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]<span class=\"NormalTextRun SCXW204808873 BCX8\">The Ibn Battuta Mall was built in 2005 on Sheikh Zayed Road. The mall has over 300 high-end stores like H&amp;M and LC Waikiki. Besides shopping, you can dine at some of the mall\u2019s <\/span><span class=\"NormalTextRun SCXW204808873 BCX8\">world-class<\/span><span class=\"NormalTextRun SCXW204808873 BCX8\"> restaurants, cafes, and dining outlets.<\/span>[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Lulu Mall&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Lulu is the largest supermarket chain in the UAE. While the Lulu Hypermarket isn\u2019t promoted as a shopping destination, it is the best place for budget shopping. You can buy home d\u00e9cor items, beauty products, spices, electronics, and other souvenirs for cheap in the mall.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Karama Centre&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]The Al Karama area has over 300 shops selling bargain products, including electronic items, home d\u00e9cor essentials, attars, garments, and even fake copies of high-end brands. The Karama Market is the best place to shop if you&#8217;re shopping on a budget. But make sure you bargain well. You can buy lamps and lanterns, dates, garments, electronics, rugs and carpets, attar, and kitchen supplies.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Souks&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Souks are traditional Arabian markets or bazaars lined with stores selling a wide range of items at budget prices. Some famous souks here include the Gold Souk, the Spice Souk, the Perfume Souk, the Textile Souk, and the many traditional souks in Meena Bazaar. The Deira Gold Souk has over 300 gold shops selling Indian and Arabic jewellery. Some of the famous shops here include Joy Alukkas and Malabar Gold. And if you\u2019re planning to buy attar or traditional perfume made without alcohol, head to the Perfume Souk. You can purchase essential oils, incense sticks, and oudh.[\/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;Meena Bazaar&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h4|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]If you are looking for elaborately embroidered Pakistani salwar suits, head to Meena Bazaar in Bur Dubai. Besides textiles, you can shop for gold and gems, shoes, accessories, perfumes, and cheap souvenirs.[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class=&#8221;hide_readless&#8221; el_id=&#8221;what-to-eat&#8221;][vc_column_inner][vc_custom_heading text=&#8221;What To Eat In Dubai?&#8221; font_container=&#8221;tag:h3|text_align:left&#8221; use_theme_fonts=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_text]Dubai being a multicultural hub, is a dream destination for foodies. You can sample some of the world\u2019s best cuisine without breaking the bank. There&#8217;s something for everyone, from French-style bistros to Italian restaurants and Thai places selling scrumptious pad Thai. Shawarma is definitely one of the cheapest and most commonly available street food in Dubai. You can find shops in every nook and corner of the city, selling chicken, beef and lamb shawarma for around AED 5. We have elaborately covered the local dishes and where to find them <a href=\"https:\/\/www.atwtravels.com\/nine-dubai-famous-food-you-must-try\/\">here<\/a>.[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner disable_element=&#8221;yes&#8221;][vc_column_inner width=&#8221;1\/3&#8243;][vc_column_text]  <div class=\"video-popup\" id=\"video-popup1\" style=\"background-image: url('https:\/\/www.atwtravels.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/maldives-tour-places.jpg');\">\n    <div class=\"play-button \"><i class=\"fa fa-play\"><\/i><\/div>\n    <div class=\"video-popup-box\">\n      <div class=\"close-button fa fa-times\"><